imageobject.caption: This is a scene from a party after Clay beat Sonny Liston for the heavyweight title. Such is the power of his celebrity, the assembled crowd are jostling around him simply to watch him eat....

imageobject.author: Photograph: Bettmann/Corbis

imageobject.author: Photograph: Gordon Parks/AP

imageobject.caption: The expressions, the simmering contempt, the outfits, the saturated colours – what’s not to love about this image of Ali and George Foreman taken before Ali’s second fight with Jerry Quarry?

imageobject.caption: In all of the photographs I’ve seen of Ali, I can’t think of any where he looks as supremely toned as this. You can almost see the sinews of his upper body tensing as he prepares to unload...

imageobject.author: Photograph: Jess Tan/AP

imageobject.author: Photograph: Harry Benson/Hulton
imageobject.caption: The perspective of this shot is what makes it work for me. Ali is towering over the photographer, dominating him with his physical presence as well as his verbal tirade. From any other angle...

imageobject.author: Photograph: Carl Fischer/Esquire
imageobject.caption: One of the most celebrated magazine front covers of all time and understandably so. Carl Fischer’s shot for Esquire was the brainchild of art director George Lois. The reference to St Sebastian...

imageobject.author: Photograph: RED/AP
imageobject.caption: In dumping George Foreman to the canvas in ‘The Rumble in the Jungle’, Ali reclaimed the heavyweight title after his long suspension for refusing to be drafted into the US Army. Admittedly...

imageobject.author: Photograph: Neil Leifer/Sports Illustrated/Getty Images
imageobject.caption: Ali’s distinctive footwork – the so-called ‘Ali shuffle’ – is rendered cleverly here using multiple exposures. The effect recalls Eadweard Muybridge’s early stop-motion experiments...

imageobject.author: Photograph: James Drake/Time & Life Pictures/Getty Image
imageobject.caption: Ali’s capacity to engage with the camera and project himself was extraordinary. A shot like this has the power to make you feel like you’re there in the back of the cab with him. It’s...

imageobject.caption: The juxtaposition between these two figures is great. Even when hunched over, Ali still dwarfs the comedian and singer Sammy Davis Jr, whom he’s teaching how to box. More than that, though,...

imageobject.author: Photograph: John Rooney/Associated Press
imageobject.caption: The most famous photo of Ali ever taken is of him standing over Sonny Liston, who appeared to have thrown their 1965 bout. It was taken by Neil Leifer and was shot in colour. Spare a thought...

imageobject.author: Photograph: Bettmann/CORBIS
imageobject.caption: Ali was 34 by the time this photograph was taken of him and Ken Norton playfully chasing one another across the field at Yankee Stadium. You don’t get fight promotions like this these days....

imageobject.author: Photograph: Walter Iooss Jr./SPORTS ILLUSTRA/Sports Illustrated
imageobject.caption: I find this image of Ali and Frazier, taken in 2003, to be profoundly melancholic . These two men, who were once so supreme and who shared such a glorious history, appear to have been defeated...

imageobject.author: Photograph: James Drake/The LIFE Picture Collection/Gett
imageobject.caption: This shot witnesses a pre-fight scene where Ali is poised with anticipation. His outline is so distinctive – it reminds me of the famed image of Ali underwater by Flip Schulke. Notice, also,...

imageobject.author: Photograph: Photoshot/Getty Images
imageobject.caption: This emotive picture was snapped when Clay beat Liston, who was unable to answer the bell for round seven of their 1964 fight. There are many fine photos of this moment taken head on but in...

imageobject.caption: In 2003 this was voted the greatest sport photo ever by the Observer. Even Neil Leifer calls it his best shot – one, he says, on which he cannot improve. He’s right. The pristine white...

metatags.og:description: Record Store Day was conceived in 2007 at a gathering of independent record store owners and employees as a way to celebrate and spread the word about the unique culture surrounding nearly 1400 independently owned record stores in the US and thousands of similar stores internationally. The first Record Store Day took place on April 19, 2008. Today there are Record Store Day participating stores on every continent except Antarctica.
